**Sec. 80001 – Exemption of Certain Assets**  
This amendment to the Higher Education Act of 1965 removes the "net value of the" requirement when calculating financial need for federal student aid. It adds exemptions for a family farm where the family resides, a small business with up to 100 employees owned by the family, and a commercial fishing business including vessels and permits. These exemptions apply starting with the 2026–2027 academic year.

---

**Sec. 81001 – Loan Limits and Termination of Graduate PLUS Loans**  
This section reduces graduate and professional student borrowing options by eliminating eligibility for Direct PLUS loans for graduate students starting July 1, 2026. It sets new annual and aggregate loan limits for Direct Unsubsidized Stafford Loans: $20,500 annually for graduate students and $50,000 for professional students. Aggregate limits are capped at $100,000 for non-professional graduate students and $200,000 for professional students, with adjustments for prior borrowing.

---

**Sec. 82001 – Loan Repayment Reforms**  
This section transitions borrowers from income contingent repayment plans to new income-based repayment plans by July 1, 2028. It establishes new standard repayment terms based on loan balance and introduces a new Repayment Assistance Plan with income-based payments. It also eliminates income contingent repayment plans and restricts future repayment options to standard or income-based plans.

---

**Sec. 82002 – Deferment and Forbearance Restrictions**  
Starting July 1, 2027, borrowers with new loans will no longer be eligible for unemployment or economic hardship deferments. Forbearance will be limited to 9 months within any 24-month period for loans originated on or after that date.

---

**Sec. 82003 – Loan Rehabilitation Expansion**  
This section doubles the number of times a borrower can rehabilitate defaulted loans from once to twice for both FFEL and Direct loans, and from once to twice for Perkins loans. It also sets a minimum monthly payment of $10 for borrowers with loans originated on or after July 1, 2027.

---

**Sec. 82004 – Public Service Loan Forgiveness Expansion**  
This amendment adds on-time payments under the new Repayment Assistance Plan to the list of qualifying payments for Public Service Loan Forgiveness, expanding eligibility for loan forgiveness.

---

**Sec. 82005 – Increased Loan Servicing Funding**  
This section allocates $1 billion in mandatory funding for the Department of Education to cover administrative costs, including loan servicing for Direct Loan programs.

---

**Sec. 83001 – Pell Grant Eligibility and Income Rules**  
This section updates Pell Grant eligibility by including foreign income for dependent and independent students starting July 1, 2026. It also introduces a new rule disqualifying students with a Student Aid Index (SAI) equal to or greater than twice the maximum Pell Grant amount.

---

**Sec. 83002 – Workforce Pell Grants**  
This creates a new Workforce Pell Grant program for students in short-term, non-degree workforce programs (150–600 clock hours, 8–15 weeks). These grants are limited to high-skill, in-demand fields and require state certification. Students cannot receive both Workforce Pell Grants and other Pell Grants simultaneously.

---

**Sec. 83003 – Increased Pell Grant Funding**  
This increases the maximum Pell Grant allocation from $2.17 billion to $12.67 billion annually, significantly expanding grant availability.

---

**Sec. 83004 – Pell Grant Exclusion for Other Aid**  
Starting July 1, 2026, students receiving non-federal grant aid (from states, institutions, or private sources) equal to or exceeding their cost of attendance will become ineligible for Pell Grants.

---

**Sec. 84001 – Program Ineligibility for Low-Earning Outcomes**  
This section introduces a new accountability measure where institutions lose eligibility for federal aid if their programs consistently produce graduates with low earnings. Programs must meet median earnings thresholds relative to working adults in similar fields. Small programs with fewer than 30 graduates get special handling. Institutions can appeal and regain eligibility after two years of ineligibility.

---

**Sec. 85001 – Delay of Borrower Defense Rule**  
This delays the implementation of the 2022 borrower defense regulations until July 1, 2035. Until then, the pre-2020 borrower defense rules are restored.

---

**Sec. 85002 – Delay of Closed School Discharge Rule**  
This delays the implementation of the 2022 closed school discharge regulations until July 1, 2035. Until then, the pre-2020 rules remain in effect.

---

**Sec. 86001 – Garden of Heroes Funding**  
This allocates $40 million to the National Endowment for the Humanities for the creation of statues honoring American heroes, as directed by previous executive orders.

---

**Sec. 87001 – Unaccompanied Alien Children Sponsor Vetting**  
This provides $300 million to the Office of Refugee Resettlement for fiscal years 2025–2028 to conduct background checks, home studies, and safety assessments for potential sponsors of unaccompanied alien children, including criminal and gang-related screenings.

